## 7. Security Requirements (acceptance-blocking)

- Client-facing auth from day one, even locally: static bearer token minimum (config-supplied), mTLS optional flag. Unauthenticated `/mcp` requests: 401, no tool listing.
- No secrets in logs, ever. Audit entries carry `credentialRef` names, never material. Add a log-scrubber test that greps output for cert thumbprint/secret patterns.
- No generic execution tool. CI check: the tool registry must fail startup if any manifest requests `type: script` params or a tool named like run/exec/invoke-command.
- Error sanitization: cmdlet exceptions are mapped to stable error codes + safe messages; raw exception text goes to the audit log only.
- Dependency pinning: MicrosoftTeams module version pinned in the Dockerfile; Renovate/Dependabot config included; upgrades are PRs with the integration suite run.
- Rate limiting per session (default 30 calls/min) to keep a runaway client from hammering a tenant into throttling.

## 8. Tool Set — Full Operational Coverage

Design intent: this is an **operational management toolset**, not just MACD execution. The target user is any M365 architect responsible for a Teams Phone environment — including ones who are *not* voice specialists. Two consequences ripple through every tool:

- **Diagnostic and reporting tools carry plain-English findings.** Composite tools return a `findings[]` array where each item has `severity`, `what` (observed state), `why` (why it matters), and `fix` (which tool or admin action remediates it). A generalist admin should be able to act on output without knowing what a dial plan is beforehand.
- **Reads and diagnostics are the majority of the catalog on purpose.** Most operational value for non-experts is "tell me what's wrong and what changed" — writes are the smaller, more guarded half.

### Phase A — Inventory & configuration reads (tier 0)
1. `get-tenant-voice-snapshot` — full config export: numbers, EV users, policies, CQ/AA topology, emergency addresses, schedules. (Onboarding discovery + pre-change backup source.)
2. `get-user-voice-config` — one user: number, policies, licenses, EV status, emergency location
3. `list-phone-numbers` — inventory w/ assignment status, number type, range, filters (e.g., unassigned only)
4. `get-callqueue-config` / 5. `get-autoattendant-config` — full object detail incl. resolved targets
6. `check-user-licensing` — EV/Calling Plan license state for a UPN + tenant SKU availability
7. `list-emergency-addresses` — validated civic addresses + locations
8. `list-voice-policies` — all voice-relevant policy types with assignment counts
9. `list-resource-accounts` — RA inventory w/ number class, license, attached CQ/AA
10. `get-schedules` — business hours + holiday schedules and which AAs reference them

### Phase B — Diagnostics & troubleshooting (tier 0) — the "why isn't this working" set
11. `diagnose-user-voice` — composite: license → EV → number → policy chain → dial plan → emergency location; ordered findings with fixes. The first tool a non-expert reaches for on "Bob can't make calls."
12. `trace-call-flow` — given a dialed number, resolve the full path: number → RA → AA menu tree → CQs → agents; flags deleted/broken/looping targets. (The tool voice experts will evangelize.)
13. `test-dialplan-number` — effective normalization of a dialed string for a given user
14. `diagnose-callqueue-health` — zero opted-in agents, unreachable overflow/timeout targets, presence-routing starvation
15. `get-pstn-usage` — PSTN call records for user/number/date range (Calling Plans + Operator Connect)
16. `get-call-quality-summary` — call quality for a user/time window via Graph callRecords; surfaces the evidence for "calls sound bad" tickets
17. `find-orphaned-objects` — RAs without numbers/licenses, AAs targeting deleted CQs, empty CQs in call paths, EV users without numbers, unassigned custom policies
18. `run-tenant-health-check` — composite misconfiguration checklist across all of the above, severity-ranked with remediation pointers. Designed to be the "run this monthly" flagship for generalist admins.

### Phase C — Reporting (tier 0)
19. `report-number-utilization` — assigned/free/aging by range and type; forecast exhaustion
20. `report-license-utilization` — voice SKUs assigned vs. available vs. wasted (licensed, never enabled)
21. `report-emergency-coverage` — voice users lacking an emergency location (compliance-critical)
22. `report-policy-assignments` — user × policy-type matrix, exportable
23. `report-change-history` — human-readable change report generated from this server's own audit log (§9)

### Phase D — Core user-level writes (tier 1–2)
24. `assign-phone-number` (add) — license check → EV enable → assign → policy set
25. `remove-phone-number` (delete, tier 2) — release to inventory/carrier pool
26. `move-number-between-users` (move, tier 2)
27. `onboard-voice-user` (add, tier 2, composite) — the full new-hire flow in one call
28. `offboard-voice-user` (delete, tier 2, composite) — strip EV, remove memberships, release number, disposition report
29. `update-callqueue-members` (tier 1) — add/remove agents
30. `update-user-calling-policies` (tier 1) — assignment from existing policies only
31. `update-user-voicemail-settings` (tier 1) — voicemail policy + per-user settings
32. `set-caller-id-assignment` (tier 1) — assign existing caller ID policy / RA substitution
33. `update-user-emergency-location` (tier 2) — existing validated addresses only

### Phase E — Shared-object writes (tier 2–3)
34. `update-callqueue-settings` (tier 2) — routing method, thresholds, overflow/timeout targets
35. `update-holiday-schedule` (tier 2) — the perennial "add the Christmas closure" operation
36. `update-autoattendant-settings` (tier 3) — menus, greetings, hours, operator target
37. `create-callqueue-from-template` / 38. `create-autoattendant-from-template` (tier 3)
39. `create-emergency-address` (tier 3) — address validation gate enforced before creation
40. `bulk-assign-numbers` (tier 3) — CSV-style batch with explicit per-call blast-radius declaration

### Phase F — Audit & server operations (tier 0, local — no tenant connection)
41. `query-audit-log` — filter this server's audit store by tenant, date range, tool, status, caller
42. `get-change-detail` — correlationId → full record incl. before/after snapshots and stage timings
43. `export-audit-report` — per-tenant, per-period change report (Markdown/CSV) suitable for handing to a customer or MSP

Not in v1 (documented as such): porting execution, Direct Routing/SBC, carrier/range ordering, tenant first-enablement, license purchasing, live call control.

